\subsection{U(1)$\times$U(1) Torus Navigation}
Having established that one-dimensional global phase rotation provides insufficient degrees of
freedom, we test whether the manifold geometry is fundamentally 1D or richer by decomposing the
512-dimensional complex embedding into two disjoint subspaces at split point ${{.SplitPoint}}$:
$$F \mapsto (e^{i\alpha_1}\cdot F_1,\; e^{i\alpha_2}\cdot F_2)$$
This promotes the symmetry group from $U(1)$ to the 2-dimensional torus $T^2 = U(1)\times U(1)$.

Sweeping a $(\alpha_1,\alpha_2)$ grid with ${{.StepDeg | f3}}^{\circ}$ resolution, the best
recorded torus gain was ${{.BestTorusGain | f4}}$, exceeding the 1D ceiling of
${{.Ceiling | f4}}$ by ${{.BestDelta | signed}}$ ($\Delta > 0$ = super-additive).
{{if .AnySuperAdditive}}Super-additivity was confirmed across at least one first-hop angle.{{else}}No first-hop angle achieved super-additivity.{{end}}

